> Verilator version
```
Verilator 4.038 2020-07-11 rev v4.036-114-g0cd4a57ad
```
Testcase
```systemverilog
// t_type_conversion_err.v
/* verilator lint_off DECLFILENAME */
module t(
  in1,
  in2,
  out
  );
/* verilator lint_on DECLFILENAME */
  input logic in1;
  input logic [1:0] in2;
  output logic [31:0] out;
  
  typedef logic[7:0] data;
  
  /* verilator lint_off WIDTH */
  assign out = data'(in1 << in2);
  /* verilator lint_on WIDTH */
  
endmodule
```
> After translated by verilator with the command:  _**verilator -Wall --sc --top-module t t_type_conversion_err.v**_, we can get the following code:
```c++
// Vt.cpp
VL_INLINE_OPT void Vt::_combo__TOP__1(Vt__Syms* __restrict vlSymsp) {
    VL_DEBUG_IF(VL_DBG_MSGF("+    Vt::_combo__TOP__1\n"); );
    Vt* const __restrict vlTOPp VL_ATTR_UNUSED = vlSymsp->TOPp;
    // Body
    VL_ASSIGN_ISI(2,vlTOPp->__Vcellinp__t__in2, vlTOPp->in2);
    VL_ASSIGN_ISI(1,vlTOPp->__Vcellinp__t__in1, vlTOPp->in1);
    VL_ASSIGN_SII(32,vlTOPp->out, (1U & ((IData)(vlTOPp->__Vcellinp__t__in1) 
                                         << (IData)(vlTOPp->__Vcellinp__t__in2))));
}
```
> I think that the following statement is wrong, what's your opinion?
```c++
VL_ASSIGN_SII(32,vlTOPp->out, (1U & ((IData)(vlTOPp->__Vcellinp__t__in1) 
                                         << (IData)(vlTOPp->__Vcellinp__t__in2))));
```
